Here's an example C program that creates a zombie process:
```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <unistd.h>

int main() {
    pid_t child_pid = fork();

    if (child_pid > 0) {
        printf("Parent process sleeping for 10 seconds...\n");
        sleep(10);
        printf("Parent process exiting...\n");
        exit(0);
    } else if (child_pid == 0) {
        printf("Child process running...\n");
        exit(0);
    } else {
        printf("Fork failed.\n");
        exit(1);
    }

    return 0;
}
```
When this program is run, the parent process will fork a child process and then sleep for 10 seconds before exiting. Meanwhile, the child process will print a message and then immediately exit. Since the child process has exited, but the parent process hasn't waited for it, the child process becomes a zombie.

To see the zombie process, you can run the program in the background and then run `ps -l` in another terminal window:
```yaml
$ gcc zombie.c -o zombie
$ ./zombie &
[1] 4280
Parent process sleeping for 10 seconds...
$ ps -l
F S   UID   PID  PPID  C PRI  NI ADDR SZ WCHAN  TTY          TIME CMD
0 S  1000  4279  1859  0  80   0 -  1916 wait   pts/0    00:00:00 bash
0 Z  1000  4280  4279  0  80   0 -     0 exit   pts/0    00:00:00 zombie <defunct>
0 R  1000  4284  1859  0  80   0 -   566 -      pts/0    00:00:00 ps
```
As you can see, the child process (with PID 4280) is listed as a zombie process with a status of "Z". To remove the zombie process, you can simply kill the parent process (with PID 4279) using the `kill` command:
```shell
$ kill -9 4279
```
This will terminate the parent process and automatically clean up the zombie child process.

