To change the width of an iframe based on the screen width, you can use the following HTML, CSS, and JavaScript code:
```
<!-- HTML code for the iframe -->
<iframe id="my-iframe" src="https://www.example.com" width="360"></iframe>

<!-- CSS code to style the iframe -->
<style>
  #my-iframe {
    display: block;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
</style>

<!-- JavaScript code to change the iframe width based on the screen width -->
<script>
  // Set the initial width of the iframe to 360px
  document.getElementById('my-iframe').width = 360;

  // Get the current screen width
  var screenWidth = window.innerWidth;

  // If the screen width is less than or equal to 720px, set the iframe width to 360px
  if (screenWidth <= 720) {
    document.getElementById('my-iframe').width = 360;
  }
  // If the screen width is greater than 720px but less than or equal to 1400px, set the iframe width to 720px
  else if (screenWidth > 720 && screenWidth <= 1400) {
    document.getElementById('my-iframe').width = 720;
  }
  // If the screen width is greater than 1400px, set the iframe width to 1400px
  else {
    document.getElementById('my-iframe').width = 1400;
  }
</script>
```
In this code, the iframe width is set to 360px by default. When the screen width is less than or equal to 720px, the iframe width is set to 360px. When the screen width is greater than 720px but less than or equal to 1400px, the iframe width is set to 720px. Finally, when the screen width is greater than 1400px, the iframe width is set to 1400px.

You can adjust the values in the JavaScript code to set the iframe width to different values based on the screen width.

