The `@Value` annotation is used in the Spring framework to inject values into fields, methods or constructor parameters of a Spring bean from a property source. The values can be hardcoded, taken from a properties file, environment variable, system properties, or from any other source of configuration data.

Here are some examples of how `@Value` can be used:

1. Injecting a value into a field:
```kotlin
@Component
public class MyComponent {

    @Value("${my.property}")
    private String myProperty;

    // ...
}
```
In this example, the value of the `my.property` property from a properties file or any other property source will be injected into the `myProperty` field of the `MyComponent` bean.

2. Injecting a value into a method:
```typescript
@Component
public class MyComponent {

    private String myProperty;

    @Value("${my.property}")
    public void setMyProperty(String myProperty) {
        this.myProperty = myProperty;
    }

    // ...
}
```
In this example, the value of the `my.property` property will be injected into the `setMyProperty` method of the `MyComponent` bean.

3. Injecting a value into a constructor parameter:
```kotlin
@Component
public class MyComponent {

    private String myProperty;

    @Autowired
    public MyComponent(@Value("${my.property}") String myProperty) {
        this.myProperty = myProperty;
    }

    // ...
}
```
In this example, the value of the `my.property` property will be injected into the constructor of the `MyComponent` bean.

Overall, `@Value` can be used to inject any type of value into a Spring bean, including strings, numbers, booleans, arrays, and more. It provides a flexible way to configure Spring beans based on the configuration data in the application.

In object-oriented programming, a reference is a variable that holds the memory address of an object in memory. A static reference and a non-static reference differ in the way they are used to access members (variables or methods) of a class.

A non-static reference is an instance-level reference that is created for each instance (object) of a class. Non-static members are associated with each instance of the class and can be accessed using a non-static reference. Non-static references are created using the new keyword and are usually accessed through instance methods.

Here is an example:
```java
public class MyClass {
    private int myVariable;

    public void setMyVariable(int value) {
        this.myVariable = value;
    }

    public int getMyVariable() {
        return myVariable;
    }
}

MyClass myInstance = new MyClass();
myInstance.setMyVariable(10);
int value = myInstance.getMyVariable(); // value = 10
```
In this example, `myInstance` is a non-static reference to an instance of `MyClass`. The `setMyVariable` and `getMyVariable` methods are instance methods, which means they can be accessed through the `myInstance` reference to set or get the value of the `myVariable` member.

A static reference, on the other hand, is a class-level reference that is shared by all instances of a class. Static members are associated with the class itself and can be accessed using a static reference. Static references are created using the class name and are usually accessed through static methods.

Here is an example:
```csharp
public class MyClass {
    private static int myVariable;

    public static void setMyVariable(int value) {
        MyClass.myVariable = value;
    }

    public static int getMyVariable() {
        return MyClass.myVariable;
    }
}

MyClass.setMyVariable(10);
int value = MyClass.getMyVariable(); // value = 10
```
In this example, `myVariable` is a static member of `MyClass`, which means it is associated with the class itself, rather than with individual instances. The `setMyVariable` and `getMyVariable` methods are static methods, which means they can be accessed through the `MyClass` reference to set or get the value of the `myVariable` member.

Overall, the key difference between a static reference and a non-static reference is that a non-static reference is associated with an instance of a class, while a static reference is associated with the class itself. This has implications for how they are used to access members of a class.

The `Logger` class is a utility class in Java that is used to log messages and events from an application. It is part of the Java Logging API and is commonly used in enterprise applications, web applications, and other types of software.

The `Logger` class provides methods for logging messages at different levels of severity, such as:

* `SEVERE`: for critical errors that cause the application to fail
* `WARNING`: for non-critical errors or warnings that do not cause the application to fail
* `INFO`: for informational messages that describe the application's state or progress
* `CONFIG`: for configuration messages that describe the application's configuration or setup
